{"topicId":"artificial-neurons-perceptron","mcqs":[{"id":"mcq-1","question":"What is a perceptron in deep learning?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A single artificial neuron that makes decisions by weighing input signals"},{"key":"B","text":"A multi-layer neural network architecture"},{"key":"C","text":"A type of activation function"},{"key":"D","text":"A gradient descent optimization algorithm"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"A perceptron is the simplest form of a neural network, consisting of a single neuron that classifies inputs by computing a weighted sum.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-2","question":"Which of the following is NOT a typical activation function used in perceptrons?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"Sigmoid"},{"key":"B","text":"ReLU"},{"key":"C","text":"Softmax"},{"key":"D","text":"Step function"}],"correctAnswer":"C","explanation":"Softmax is typically used in the output layer for multi-class classification, not as a perceptron activation function.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-3","question":"In the perceptron learning algorithm, when is the weight vector updated?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"After every misclassified sample"},{"key":"B","text":"After processing all training samples"},{"key":"C","text":"Only at the beginning of training"},{"key":"D","text":"When the learning rate is zero"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"The perceptron algorithm updates weights immediately after each misclassification to correct the error.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-4","question":"What is the Delta Rule in perceptron learning?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A rule that updates weights proportional to the error between desired and actual output"},{"key":"B","text":"A method to count neurons in a network"},{"key":"C","text":"A technique for initializing bias values"},{"key":"D","text":"A rule for selecting learning rate"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"The Delta Rule uses gradient descent to adjust weights based on the difference between predicted and target outputs.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-5","question":"Why cannot a single perceptron solve the XOR problem?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"XOR requires a non-linear decision boundary which a single perceptron cannot represent"},{"key":"B","text":"XOR has too many inputs for a perceptron"},{"key":"C","text":"Perceptrons cannot handle bias for XOR"},{"key":"D","text":"XOR requires continuous activation functions"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"A single perceptron can only create linear decision boundaries, but XOR requires a non-linear boundary to separate its outputs.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-6","question":"What does the bias term in a perceptron do?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"Shifts the decision boundary away from the origin"},{"key":"B","text":"Controls the learning rate"},{"key":"C","text":"Reduces the number of inputs"},{"key":"D","text":"Increases the number of weights"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"Bias allows the decision boundary to be shifted, enabling the perceptron to classify data that is not linearly separable through the origin.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-7","question":"What is the primary advantage of a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) over a single perceptron?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"MLPs can learn non-linear patterns and solve problems like XOR"},{"key":"B","MLPs always train faster than single perceptrons"},{"key":"C","text":"MLPs require less training data"},{"key":"D","text":"MLPs cannot overfit"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"MLPs use hidden layers with non-linear activation functions, allowing them to learn complex non-linear relationships.","difficulty":"hard"},{"id":"mcq-8","question":"Under what condition is the perceptron learning algorithm guaranteed to converge?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"When the training data is linearly separable"},{"key":"B","text":"When the learning rate is greater than 1"},{"key":"C","text":"When using sigmoid activation function"},{"key":"D","text":"When training data has no bias term"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"The perceptron convergence theorem guarantees that the algorithm will find a solution if the training data is linearly separable.","difficulty":"hard"}]}